04844nam a22007455i 9780674419971DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979683878  a97806744199717 a10.4159/harvard.97806744199712doi  a(DE-B1597)427276  a(OCoLC)871257766  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aB77b.D43513 2014eb 7aPHI0150002bisacsh04a128/.22231 aDescombes, Vincent, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Institutions of Meaning :bA Defense of Anthropological Holism /cVincent Descombes. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the English Translation -- tpart I. Intentionalist Conceptions of Mind -- t1. The Intentionality of the Mental -- t2. The Paradox of the Intentional Object -- t3. A Holistic Conception of Intentionality -- tpart II. The Anthropological Holism of the Mental -- t4. The Question of Holism -- t5. The Illusion of Collective Individuals -- t6. The Order of Meaning -- t7. The Logic of Relations -- t8. The Subject of Triadic Relations -- t9. Essays on the Gift -- t10. Objective Mind -- t11. Distinguishing Thoughts -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHolism grows out of the philosophical position that an object or phenomenon is more than the sum of its parts. And yet analysis--a mental process crucial to human comprehension--involves breaking something down into its components, dismantling the whole in order to grasp it piecemeal and relationally. Wading through such quandaries with grace and precision, The Institutions of Meaning guides readers to a deepened appreciation of the entity that ultimately enables human understanding: the mind itself. This major work from one of France's most innovative philosophers goes against the grain of analytic philosophy in arguing for the view known as anthropological holism. Meaning is not fundamentally a property of mental representations, Vincent Descombes says. Rather, it arises out of thought that is holistic, embedded in social existence, and bound up with the common practices that shape the way we act and talk. To understand what an individual "believes" or "wants"--to apply psychological words to a person--we must take into account the full historical and institutional context of a person's life. But how can two people share the same thought if they do not share the same system of belief? Descombes solves this problem by developing a logic of relations that explains the ability of humans to analyze structures based on their parts. Integrating insights from anthropology, linguistics, and social theory, The Institutions of Meaning pushes philosophy forward in bold new directions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHolism. 0aPhilosophy. 0aSense (Philosophy). 0aSpirit. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Mind & Body.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2014z9783110370393oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441997140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674419971423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674419971.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  